# Logic and Arguments: Exercises

## Identifying Premises and Conclusions

::: example
> Waging war is always wrong, because it involves killing human beings.
:::

```{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice points=10}
1 The conclusion of this argument is:
| *Waging war is always wrong.
| Waging war involves killing human beings.
| Killing human beings is always wrong.
| Waging war is always wrong because it involves killing human beings.
2 A premise of this argument is:
| Waging war is always wrong.
| *Waging war involves killing human beings.
| Waging war is always wrong because it involves killing human beings.
```

```{.QualitativeProblem .ShortAnswer give-credit="onSubmission" points=10}
3 Rewrite the argument in standard form.
```

::: example
> In 1950, the population of the world was about 2.5 billion. In 1967, the
population of the world was almost 3.5 billion. In 1980, the population of the
world was almost 5.5 billion. In 2007, it was 6.6 billion. So, the population
of the world has grown both steadily and rapidly since 1950.
:::

```{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice points=10}
4 The conclusion of this argument is:
| In 1950, the population of the world was about 2.5 billion. 
| In 1967, the population of the world was almost 3.5 billion. 
| In 1980, the population of the world was almost 5.5 billion.
| In 2007, the population of the world was almost 6.6 billion.
| *The population of the world has grown both steadily and rapidly since 1950.
```

```{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleSelection points=10}
5 The premises of this argument are (select all correct answers):
| *In 1950, the population of the world was about 2.5 billion. 
| *In 1967, the population of the world was almost 3.5 billion. 
| *In 1980, the population of the world was almost 5.5 billion.
| *In 2007, the population of the world was almost 6.6 billion.
| The population of the world has grown both steadily and rapidly since 1950.
```

```{.QualitativeProblem .ShortAnswer give-credit="onSubmission" points=10}
6 Rewrite the argument in standard form.
```

::: example
> Either James died because he was shot or James died because he was hanged.
Since James didn't die because he was hanged, he died because he was shot.
:::

```{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleSelection points=10}
7 The premises of this argument are (select all correct answers):
| *Either James died because he was shot or James died because he was hanged.
| James died because he was hanged.
| Since James didn't die because he was hanged, he died because he was shot.
| *James didn't die because he was hanged
| James died because he was shot.
```

```{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice points=10}
8 The conclusion of this argument is: 
| Either James died because he was shot or James died because he was hanged.
| James died because he was hanged.
| Since James didn't die because he was hanged, he died because he was shot.
| James didn't die because he was hanged
| *James died because he was shot.
```
 
```{.QualitativeProblem .ShortAnswer give-credit="onSubmission" points=10}
9 Rewrite the argument in standard form.
```

::: example
> If it is permissible for humans to eat animals, then it would be permissible
for super-intelligent extraterrestrials to eat humans. But that wouldn't be
permissible. So it isn't permissible for humans to eat animals.
:::


```{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice points=10}
10 The conclusion of this argument is: 
| If it is permissible for humans to eat animals, then it would be permissible for super-intelligent extraterrestrials to eat humans. 
| It is permissible for humans to eat animals
| It would be permissible for super-intelligent extraterrestrials to eat humans. 
| It wouldn't be permissible for super-intelligent extraterrestrials to eat humans.
| *It isn't permissible for humans to eat animals.
```

```{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleSelection points=10}
11 The premises of this argument are (select all correct answers):
| *If it is permissible for humans to eat animals, then it would be permissible for super-intelligent extraterrestrials to eat humans. 
| It is permissible for humans to eat animals
| It would be permissible for super-intelligent extraterrestrials to eat humans. 
| *It wouldn't be permissible for super-intelligent extraterrestrials to eat humans.
| It isn't permissible for humans to eat animals.
``` 

```{.QualitativeProblem .ShortAnswer give-credit="onSubmission" points=10}
12 Rewrite the argument in standard form.
```

::: example
> Blindly clicking answers to these exercises until you get them right will get
you *points* but not *practice*. But you need practice in order to do well on
the unit test. So you should not blindly click answers to these exercises
until you get them right.
:::


```{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice points=10}
13 The conclusion of this argument is: 
| Blindly clicking answers to these exercises until you get them right will get you *points* but not *practice*. 
| You need practice in order to do well on the unit test. 
| *You shouldn't blindly click answers to these exercises until you get them right.
```

```{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleSelection points=10}
14 The premises of this argument are (select all correct answers):
| *Blindly clicking answers to these exercises until you get them right will get you *points* but not *practice*. 
| *You need practice in order to do well on the unit test. 
| You shouldn't blindly click answers to these exercises until you get them right.
``` 

```{.QualitativeProblem .ShortAnswer give-credit="onSubmission" points=10}
15 Rewrite the argument in standard form.
```


::: example
> Be a doctor! You've got the talent. You would enjoy the work. You could help
many people. And you could make a lot of money!
:::

```{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice points=10}
16 The conclusion of this argument is: 
| *You ought to be a doctor.
| You have the talent to be a doctor.
| You would enjoy the work of a doctor.
| You could help many people as a doctor.
| You could make a lot of money as a doctor.
```

```{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleSelection points=10}
17 The premises of this argument are (select all correct answers):
| You ought to be a doctor.
| *You have the talent to be a doctor.
| *You would enjoy the work of a doctor.
| *You could help many people as a doctor.
| *You could make a lot of money as a doctor.
``` 

```{.QualitativeProblem .ShortAnswer give-credit="onSubmission" points=10}
18 Rewrite the argument in standard form.
```

::: example
> Capital punishment is wrong because all killing is wrong.
:::

``` {.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice points="10"}
19 The conclusion of this argument is: 
| Capital punishment is wrong because all killing is wrong.
| *Capital punishment is wrong.
| All killing is wrong.
```

```{.QualitativeProblem .MultipleSelection points=10}
20 The premises of this argument are (select all correct answers):
| Capital punishment is wrong because all killing is wrong.
| Capital punishment is wrong.
| *All killing is wrong.
```

```{.QualitativeProblem .ShortAnswer give-credit="onSubmission" points=10}
21 Rewrite the argument in standard form.
```

## Identifying Implicit Premises

::: example
> Be a doctor! You've got the talent. You would enjoy the work. You could help
many people. And you could make a lot of money!
:::

``` {.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice points="10"}
22 Which of the following is plausibly an implicit premise of this argument?
| Talented people should become doctors.
| Being a doctor is a lot of work.
| *You should choose a line of work that you would enjoy.
| You could make a lot of money as a doctor.
```

::: example
> Only fruit evolved to be eaten, so it is morally impermissible to eat anything
but fruit.
:::

``` {.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice points="10"}
23 Which of the following is plausibly an implicit premise of this argument?
| *It is morally impermissible to eat things that didn't evolve to be eaten.
| Fruit evolved to be eaten.
| Many fruits are edible.
```

::: example
> We shouldn't defund the police, because we need the police to keep our
communities safe.
:::

``` {.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice points="10"}
24 Which of the following is plausibly an implicit premise of this argument?
| The police don't harm our communities.
| We shouldn't defund the police.
| *We should do what is needed to keep our communities safe.
```

::: example
> Science tells us that objects that appear solid, like tables and chairs, are
mostly empty space. So they aren't really solid.
:::

``` {.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice points="10"}
25 Which of the following is plausibly an implicit premise of this argument?
| Not everything is as it appears.
| *To be solid is to fill up the space you occupy.
| It is important to trust scientists.
| If something is mostly empty space, it appears solid.
```

::: example
People disagree about what is beautiful, so beauty is subjective.
:::

``` {.QualitativeProblem .MultipleChoice points="10"}
26 Which of the following is plausibly an implicit premise of this argument?
| Everything is subjective.
| When two people disagree about what is beautiful, at least one of them is wrong.
| *When two people disagree about what is beautiful, neither person is wrong.
| Beauty is in the eye of the perceiver.
```


